name: Clean up a Linux filesystem
description: Procedure that describes how to cleanup a filesystem of a Linux Server

steps.description: Login to HOSTNAME using a terminal emulator

Check the remaining space on the filesystem.

Run the following command:

df -k

if the results returned looks like this:

Filesystem              1K-blocks      Used Available Use% Mounted on
/dev/mapper/system-root  15320532  10744612   3797680  74% /
/dev/mapper/appvg-apps   61923324  61923324    61923324 100% FILESYSTEM
/dev/sda1                  154691     37620    109084  26% /boot

the FILESYSTEM file system  has no space left.

Delete “safe” files from the file system.

Run the following commands to remove “safe” files:

export FILESYSTEM=FILESYSTEM
find $FILESYSTEM -depth -type f -name "*.tmp” -delete
find $FILESYSTEM -depth -type f -name "*.dmp” -delete
find$FILESYSTEM -depth -type f -name “*.log” -mtime +30 -delete


Run the following commands to empty the trash should it exist for /opt ($FILESYSTEM)

cd $FILESYSTEM

ls -al

Identify the .Trash* directory and delete all files by running the following commands. Note - do not do this if the .Trash* directory does not exist!
cd .Trash*
find . -type f -delete

Empty or purge temporary file system and/or directory

Run the following commands:

rm -rf /tmp/*
rm -rf /temp/*

Check if the problem still exists. Run the following command.

df -k

if the results returned looks like this:

Filesystem              1K-blocks      Used Available Use% Mounted on
/dev/mapper/system-root  15320532  10744612   3797680  74% /
/dev/mapper/appvg-apps   61923324  49329396   9448408  84% FILESYSTEM
/dev/sda1                  154691     37620    109084  26% /boot

space on the FILESYSTEM  file system has been recovered and you can end this runbook. If no or minimal change follow the instructions in the next step.

Gather information about the top 10 space consuming directories

Run the following command to establish the top 10 space consuming directories. Results returned in Megabytes(MB)

du -hsm FILESYSTEM/* | sort -nr | head -n 10

The output could look similar to below identifying important information for the next level support analyst.

Escalate the issue to the next support level

Attach the information gathered in the previous step to the escalation process and compete the runbook. Further analysis will be required to resolve the issue or the file system being investigated needs to be extended accordingly.
